{{Infobox organization | name = The Pan-Africa Mosquito Control Association (PAMCA) | image = PAMCA logo.png | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = PAMCA logo | formerly = | founder = | members = 100+<ref name=PublicHealthJournal /> | established = October 3rd, 2012 (Kenyan chapter)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kemri.org/index.php/home-mainmenu-1/27-kemri-articles/281-kenyan-chapter-of-the-pan-african-mosquito-control-association-pamca-has-been-launched|title=Kenyan Chapter of the Pan African Mosquito Control Association (PAMCA) has been launched|work=kemri.org|accessdate=12 October 2015}}</ref> | leader_title = President | leader_name = Charles Mbogo<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitalfm.co.ke/news/2012/10/kenya-must-change-tact-to-tackle-malaria-expert/|title=Kenya must change tact to tackle malaria - expert|last=Ndonga|first=Wambui|date=3 October 2012|publisher=Capital News|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> | staff = | website = http://www.pamca.org }} The '''Pan-Africa Mosquito Control Association (PAMCA)''' is an international organization of research scientists dedicated to vector control and elimination of diseases like malaria.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pamca.org/new/about/|title=About {{!}} PAMCA|publisher=PAMCA|website=pamca.org|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> The organization also aims to spread information on the study of mosquitoes<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2013/10/13/imp03.asp|title=Thorns on the Side: a potential lifesaver|publisher=Sunday Observer|date=13 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131019131249/http://www.sundayobserver.lk/2013/10/13/imp03.asp|archive-date=19 October 2013}}</ref> and connect Africans from across the continent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailynews.co.tz/index.php/home-news/42958-many-malaria-sufferers-are-oblivious-to-health-status|title=Many malaria sufferers are oblivious to health status|first=Ludovick|last=Kazoka|date=8 October 2015|accessdate=12 October 2015|publisher=[[Daily News (Tanzania)|Daily News]]}}</ref> PAMCA was first established in Kenya, and has chapter offices located in Tanzania and Nigeria.<ref name=PublicHealthJournal>{{cite journal |title=Malaria – Africa’s modern scourge |author=Charles M. Mbogo |journal=Public Health Journal |url=http://ehrengut.de/CD%20program%20files/PHJ_26-2015.pdf |date=October 2015}}</ref>
PAMCA works with organizations including [[Kenya Medical Research Institute|KEMRI]] and the National Institute for Medical Research (NIMR) in Tanzania to form networks and collaborate on research projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201510080184.html|title=Africa: Malaria Still Remains Continent's Top Killer|date=7 October 2015|last=Odunga|first=Maureen|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> They also organize conferences where entomologists discuss topics in mosquito-borne diseases such as [[dengue]], [[malaria]], and [[yellow fever]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/africa/2014-10/03/c_133689634.htm|date=3 October 2014|title=Global researchers to meet in Kenya for mosquito conference|website=xinhuanet.com|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/884712.shtml|title=Kenya calls for new efforts to battle malaria|publisher=Global Times|date=6 October 2014|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref>
