[[File:The Evening World re Sullivan Ordinance.jpg|400px|thumb|Making fun of the ordinance in [[The Evening World]] in 1908]] The '''Sullivan Ordinance''' was a [[Local ordinance|municipal law]] passed on January 21, 1908, in [[New York City]] by the board of aldermen, barring the management of a public place from allowing women to smoke within their venue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1908/01/21/archives/no-public-smoking-by-women-now-the-sullivan-ordinance-to-be-passed.html|title=NO PUBLIC SMOKING BY WOMEN NOW|date=1908-01-21|work=The New York Times|page=1|accessdate=2008-06-22}}</ref> The ordinance did not bar women from smoking in general nor did the ordinance bar women from smoking in public, only public places. Right after the ordinance was enacted, on January 22, Katie Mulcahey, the only person cited for breaking this ordinance, was fined $5 for smoking in public and arrested for refusing to pay the fine; however, the ordinance itself did not mention fines nor does it ban women from smoking in public. She was released the next day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Today in history: Jan. 21|url=http://amestrib.com/sections/opinion/columns/today-history-jan-21.html|accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref> The mayor at the time, [[George B. McClellan Jr.]], vetoed the ordinance two weeks later.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://weeklywire.com/ww/10-13-97/nash_cover.html|title=The Smoldering Fire|last=Sims|first=Michael|date=1997-10-13|work=[[Nashville Scene]]|publisher=City Press|accessdate=2008-06-22}}</ref>
